<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#128188; Overhead Cost</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 24th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      Overhead is the cost of keeping the whole operation alive, the kind you
      cannot pin to any single sale: rent, admin, insurance, the lights staying
      on. It quietly supports everything yet shows up on no specific invoice.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#128663; Example:</strong> car insurance. You pay the premium
      whether you drive zero miles or ten thousand, so it is a
      <strong>fixed cost</strong>. But for a business it also covers every trip at
      once and ties to no single delivery, so it is also
      <strong>overhead</strong>. Same bill, two different questions: fixed asks
      "does this change with how much I do?", overhead asks "can I trace this to
      one sale?"
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">Mood: Counting | Quest: Keep the Lights On</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#finance</span>
    <span class="tag">#costs</span>
    <span class="tag">#business</span>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#127919; Survivorship Bias</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 24th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      Survivorship bias is studying the winners and quietly forgetting the
      wreckage that never made the highlight reel. We judge the odds by the few
      who made it, not the crowd who tried the same thing and vanished. Before
      copying a success story, go count the people who took the same path and
      lost.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#127891; Example:</strong> "He is rich and he dropped out of
      college, so college must be a waste." Maybe. But for every famous dropout
      who struck it big, thousands quit and stayed broke; they just never get the
      interview. You are hearing from the one survivor, not the crowd behind him
      who made the same bet and lost.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>&#127963;&#65039; Example:</strong> "Look how they built things to
      last back then." We admire the Roman temples and stone cathedrals still
      standing and assume the past simply built better. We forget the countless
      flimsy buildings from the same era that crumbled centuries ago. Only the
      strong ones survived long enough to impress us.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">Mood: Skeptical | Quest: Count the Missing</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#mindset</span>
    <span class="tag">#psychology</span>
    <span class="tag">#decisionmaking</span>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#9876;&#65039; Last Man Standing Mindset</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 24th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      The last man standing mindset is betting on endurance over fireworks. Most
      races are not won by the fastest runner, but by the one still moving when
      everyone else sat down, the way the tortoise beat the hare by refusing to
      stop. Intensity burns bright and burns out; consistency compounds.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#128214; Example:</strong> in <em>The Psychology of Money</em>,
      Morgan Housel argues that survival beats brilliance. The people who come
      out ahead are rarely the ones with the best single run, but the ones who
      never got knocked out, so time could quietly do the heavy lifting.
      Avoiding ruin matters more than chasing the spectacular.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="book-quote">
      <p>"But you need short-term paranoia to keep you alive long enough to exploit long-term optimism."</p>
      <cite>Morgan Housel, The Psychology of Money</cite>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">Mood: Stubborn | Quest: Outlast</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#mindset</span>
    <span class="tag">#discipline</span>
    <span class="tag">#money</span>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#128176; Fixed Cost</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 24th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      A fixed cost is a cost that stays the same even when your usage or
      activity changes. It does not care if you had a busy month, a slow month,
      or did almost nothing. The bill still shows up.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is why fixed costs matter: they create a baseline you must cover
      before anything feels profitable, flexible, or free.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#128663; Example:</strong> car insurance. Even if you do not drive
      the car this month, you may still have to pay the insurance premium. In
      personal budgeting, that makes it a fixed expense. In a business, it can
      also be overhead because it supports operations indirectly.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">Mood: Practical | Quest: Know the Baseline</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#finance</span>
    <span class="tag">#costs</span>
    <span class="tag">#business</span>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#129504; Sunk Cost Fallacy</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 23rd 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      The sunk cost fallacy is when you keep choosing something because of
      what you already spent, even when the next move no longer makes sense.
      Time, money, and effort that are already gone cannot be rescued by
      losing more time, money, and effort.
    </p>
    <p>
      The better question is simple:
      <strong>If I were starting fresh today, would I still choose this?</strong>
      If the answer is no, quitting is not failure. It is making room for a
      better bet.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#127916; Example:</strong> you buy a movie ticket, sit down, and
      realize after twenty minutes that the movie is terrible. Staying for two
      more hours will not make the ticket cheaper. Leaving gives you the
      evening back.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">Mood: Clear | Quest: Choose Forward</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#mindset</span>
    <span class="tag">#decisionmaking</span>
    <span class="tag">#psychology</span>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#129522; How to Get Whatever You Want</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 20th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      <strong>Ask!</strong> 
      <br>I’ve been watching an old Jim Rohn talk called
      <a
        href="https://youtu.be/uOcKF-aLHyw"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >How to Get Whatever You Want</a
      >.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>1. Asking is the beginning of receiving.</strong> It starts
      a process you can't fully see, mental and emotional. Like flipping a
      switch and hearing machinery kick on somewhere in the back. You
      don't need to understand the wiring to use the switch.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>2. Receiving isn't the problem. Failing to ask is.</strong>
      His line that got me: "good worker, poor asker." The guy who shows
      up every single day but never once wrote his goals down. Hit a
      little too close.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>3. Abundance is an ocean, not a ration.</strong> Success
      isn't behind a window that sells out before you reach the front. The
      ocean is right there. The only question is whether you walked up
      with a teaspoon or a bucket. Time to trade the teaspoon for a
      bucket.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>Then he splits asking in two.</p>
    <p>
      <strong>Ask with intelligence</strong>: don't mumble. How wide, how
      high, how soon, what size, what color, how much. The sharper you
      describe a goal, the harder it pulls you, like a magnet.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Ask with faith</strong>: believe you'll get it the way a kid
      believes, before adulthood trains you to be skeptical.
    </p>
    <p>
      The whole hour folds into one sentence I'm keeping:
      <em>make plans like an adult, believe in them like a child.</em>
      He says give it 90 days. You can always go back to the old way. The
      world admires the doers.
    </p>
    <p>
      The entire lecture builds to a single-word strategy:
      <strong>Ask</strong>. It sounds basic until he unpacks why most
      people completely fail at it.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">&#127775; Mood: Motivated | Quest: Ask Bigger</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#mindset</span>
    <span class="tag">#jimrohn</span>
    <span class="tag">#goals</span>
  </div>
</article>

